There are several plants that your cats will absolutely adore if you add them to the garden. These include:
Cat grass (Dactylis glomerata) – this is great for chewing on to aid digestion. It is also loved by dogs, rabbits, and guinea pigs. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/16\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/16\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Lemongrass – the smell intrigues many cats. If you're growing it for yourself, grow another bunch for the cats because they will probably chew it. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/73\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/73\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Catnip (Nepeta cataria) – the plant that cats will love to roll in. When dried, it makes excellent stuffing for toys. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/36\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/36\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Catmint (Nepeta x faassenii) – another beloved rolling-in plant. This can also be used dried in cat toys. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fa\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fa\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Mint family – most members of the mint family entice cats. Mice don't like peppermint though, so this can also help to keep mice away from the garden. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/33\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet5.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/33\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet5.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Pennyroyal (Mentha pulegium) – this appeals to many cats. As an added bonus, you can use it to make a flea repellent. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a3\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet6.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a3\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet6.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Valerian (Valeriana officinalis) – cats enjoy playing with the foliage and flowers. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/14\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet7.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/14\/Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet7.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Pet-Friendly-Garden-Step-1Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

